# Build the retro writer

## Step

Resolved when: (1) an Inngest event (e.g. `memory/retro.requested`)
carrying pointers (brief path, session id, repo) triggers a condenser
function that reads the closed brief + its steps' Result sections and
writes one retro `.svx` into the retros store the curator reads
(`dark-wizard/.brain/resources/retros/`); (2) claude/codex/pi hooks can
fire that event on demand (hook wiring documented; at minimum a
one-liner CLI/script an agent can call at effort close); (3) the noise
bar from the [decision](../memory-system-repair/decide-retro-writer.svx)
is enforced: retros only for efforts with real decisions or multi-step
work, and the output must say what changed durable behavior, not
re-narrate the ledger; (4) one real retro exists as proof — generated
from the closed
[memory-system-review brief](../memory-system-review/memory-system-review-brief.svx).
Serialized behind the retirement migration (same repo surface).

## Result (2026-07-17)

Built the hook-facing retro writer without touching or deploying the live worker.

- Added typed event `memory/retro.requested` and host function `memory-retro-writer`.
- The writer resolves relative step links from the brief's `## Decision ledger`, reads only each linked step's `## Result` section, and rejects briefs that are not closed/done.
- The deterministic noise guard skips efforts with fewer than three linked steps and no ledger entries. It emits OTel warn action `memory.retro.skipped` with `noise_bar_not_met` before inference.
- Shared `infer()` performs the source-grounded condensation with tools/extensions off and strict JSON output. Code, not the model, owns frontmatter, section headings, receipt links, slug/month naming, and the final atomic write.
- Added `joelclaw retro <brief-path> [--session-id <id>] [--repo <path>] [--requested-by <name>]` as the one-line hook surface.
- Production output is fixed at `~/Code/joelhooks/dark-wizard/.brain/resources/retros/<brief-slug>-<yyyy-mm>.svx`. This pass wrote only `/tmp/joelclaw-memory-system-review-retro-2026-07-17.svx`.

Changed files:

- `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/memory/retro-writer.ts`
- `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/memory/retro-writer.test.ts`
- `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/client.ts`
- `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/index.host.ts`
- `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/index.ts`
- `packages/cli/src/commands/retro.ts`
- `packages/cli/src/commands/retro.test.ts`
- `packages/cli/src/cli.ts`

Verification:

- `bun test packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/memory/retro-writer.test.ts` — 5 pass.
- `bun test packages/cli/src/commands/retro.test.ts` — 2 pass.
- Focused Biome check across all changed code — pass.
- `bunx tsc --noEmit` — pass.
- `bun packages/cli/src/cli.ts retro --help` — pass; command and options render.
- Real condenser dry-run against `../memory-system-review/memory-system-review-brief.svx` — wrote scratch only; 7 linked steps and 7 ledger entries.

### Generated scratch retro

```md
---
title: "Memory System Review: the whole loop, mapped and graded retro"
type: "resource"
created_at: "2026-07-17"
privacy: "private"
---

# What happened

A receipt-backed MDSvX review now maps and grades the full memory loop plus 11 peripheral stores. It confirms that capture, curation, delivery, reaction grading, and reuse of grades operate end to end, while dreams, retros, graph privacy, delivery policy, and several peripheral stores remain degraded or missing. The review and the Observer Brain were published successfully on the wiki.

# What it means

The core loop is real and demonstrably closed—Joel’s reaction changes the history used by the next memory judgment—but reliability is uneven. The review exposes concrete priorities, especially the graph’s sensitive-metadata boundary, the 71.38 GB run-capture outbox, split delivery paths, dream starvation, and the absent retro writer. This effort diagnosed and prioritized those risks; it did not fix them.

# What changed durable behavior

The `observer` Brain is now a registered wiki root, making its 23 pages part of the published knowledge interface. `.brain/resources/memory-system.svx` is now the canonical review surface, with a stated practice to regenerate it from a fresh survey after material system changes rather than patching verdicts manually. Two Observer pages were corrected to render under MDSvX. **No core memory runtime behavior changed.**

